NCP-X (Nexus Control Propulsor - Experimental) Final Simulation Blueprint

Document Version: 5.0 (Uncertainty-Aware Modeling Framework)
Classification: Theoretical Research & Simulation Model
Date: 2026-01-10
Issuing Authority: Advanced Propulsion Analysis Group

Core Declaration: This document defines a computational proving ground for autonomous propulsion. All components are high-fidelity models with explicitly labeled confidence levels, forming a closed-loop simulation to test the core hypothesis that intelligent control can overcome internalized design penalties. No physical hardware exists.

---

1. Executive Summary: The Simulation Hypothesis

The NCP-X is a theory of operation, instantiated in code. Its purpose is to test whether a propulsion system governed by a POMDP, inferring hidden degradation from synthetic sensors, can achieve greater simulated mission reliability (P_success > 99%) than a traditional redline-shutdown controller, despite being burdened by the high thermodynamic density and partial observability of a monolithic design.

The framework's credibility is governed by a triage system:

Â· ðŸ”µ Validated Model: Foundational physics with low uncertainty.
Â· ðŸŸ¡ Parametric Model: Empirical correlations scaled to extreme regimes; medium uncertainty.
Â· ðŸ”´ Hypothetical Model: Novel formulations based on literature extrapolation; high uncertainty.

Final Benchmark: In 10,000 Monte Carlo runs of the simulated 480-second Mars ascent, the NCP-X autonomous controller must exceed a 99% success rate, outperforming a traditional controller by a minimum of 10 percentage points.

